\begin{align*}
\sqrt{a^2 + b^2} &= r + 1,\\
\sqrt{(a-2)^2 + b^2} &= 7 - r.
\end{align*}Adding these two equations, we get \[\sqrt{a^2+b^2}+\sqrt{(a-2)^2+b^2} = 8.\]
Since this doesn’t simplify too nicely, we will recreate the angle bisector. Reflect $(7,0)$ over the $y$-axis to get $(-7, 0)$; we now have an AAS situation. The angle bisector is the locus of centers of circles tangent to both circles.
[asy]unitsize(3mm);
